Based on the search results, I found several code examples demonstrating how to use `qe.project.getActiveSequence()` with the razor method and timecode handling in ExtendScript for Adobe Premiere Pro. Here's what I found:

## ExtendScript Code Examples for `qe.project.getActiveSequence()` with Razor and Timecode

### Basic Razor Cut Example

After a long time of searching, users discovered it was about calling the RAZOR method. Here is sample working code that enables the Quality Engineering library, gets the active QE sequence, and uses the CTI (Current Time Indicator) timecode in the format "00:00:03:38" for the razor operation.

```javascript
// Enable Quality Engineering library
app.enableQE();

// Get the active QE sequence
var sqe = qe.project.getActiveSequence();

// Get the playertime in timecode format (e.g., "00:00:03:38")
var playerTime = sqe.CTI.timecode;

// QE has a razor method that can be called on a sequence object
// Cut only on a specific track
sqe.getVideoTrackAt(0).razor(playerTime);
```

### Full Razor Example with Timecode Conversion

A more comprehensive example shows how to convert marker time to the "HH:MM:SS:FF" format and apply the razor to all video and audio tracks:

```javascript
function addCutAtMarker(marker) {
    var sqe = qe.project.getActiveSequence();
    var timecode = marker.start.seconds;

    // Convert to "HH:MM:SS:FF" format
    var hours = Math.floor(timecode / 3600);
    var minutes = Math.floor((timecode - (hours * 3600)) / 60);
    var seconds = Math.floor(timecode - (hours * 3600) - (minutes * 60));
    var frames = Math.floor((timecode - Math.floor(timecode)) * 24); // Assuming 24 fps
    var timecodeString = padNumber(hours, 2) + ":" + padNumber(minutes, 2) + ":" + padNumber(seconds, 2) + ":" + padNumber(frames, 2);

    // Apply cut to all video tracks
    for (var i = 0; i < sqe.numVideoTracks; i++) {
        var videoTrack = sqe.getVideoTrackAt(i);
        videoTrack.razor(timecodeString, true);
    }

    // Apply cut to all audio tracks
    for (var i = 0; i < sqe.numAudioTracks; i++) {
        var audioTrack = sqe.getAudioTrackAt(i);
        audioTrack.razor(timecodeString, true);
    }
}
```

### Using Time Object Formatting (from pymiere/ExtendScript)

The razor method requires a string timecode argument specifying when to cut the sequence. You can format a Time object to a timecode string using the sequence's video frame rate and display format settings.

### Available CTI Properties

The active sequence's CTI (Current Time Indicator) provides multiple formats: `activeSequence.CTI.secs` for seconds, `activeSequence.CTI.frames` for frames, `activeSequence.CTI.ticks` for ticks, and `activeSequence.CTI.timecode` for the string timecode format.

### Important Notes

The PPro ExtendScript QE DOM is officially unsupported and undocumented, with no additional work planned on it.(no content)There's no cut function in the standard ExtendScript API. The QE DOM has a `razor(string, bool, bool)` method on sequence and track objects.


