# Discussion Summary: Performing Cuts from Script in Adobe Premiere Pro

## Initial Question
A user asked how to cut clips from a script in a Premiere Pro panel, seeking methods to trim the last second off a clip and extend duration to the next clip.

## Adobe Employee Response
An Adobe employee (Bruce Bullis) stated: "There's no cut function; you'd need to change the end point of the trackItem (clip)."

## Code Example Provided
The employee later provided this solution:
```javascript
var myClip = app.project.sequences[0].videoTracks[0].clips[0];
if (myClip){
    var oldEnd = myClip.end;
    if (oldEnd){
        oldEnd.seconds = oldEnd.seconds + 3;
        myClip.end = oldEnd;
    }
}
```

This demonstrates modifying a clip's endpoint by adjusting the seconds property rather than using a dedicated cut function.

## Alternative Workaround
Another user shared an approach using subclips: "we can use this: app.project.rootItem.children[index].createSubClip(name, startTime, endTime, hasHardBoundaries, takeAudio, takeVideo); and than insert this clipped project item to sequence track"

## QE DOM Method
A user mentioned the Quality Engineering DOM has a "razor" method on sequence/track objects but reported difficulty implementing it successfully.

## Key Takeaway
Adobe's ExtendScript API requires manipulating clip properties directly rather than calling a dedicated cut method.

